On Rapa Nui, Styloniscus manuvaka sp. n. is presently restricted to the cave environment, but is not troglomorphic (cave-adapted). This animal was detected within the fern-moss gardens (entrance zone) of three caves, but also occurred within the twilight and cave deep zones. This species was not detected during the surface sampling work conducted in 2009, nor has it been identified during previous invertebrate inventory work (e.g., Fuentes 1914 , Olalquiaga 1946 , Kuschel 1963 ,
Campos and Pena 1973
). The species also occurs on Rapa Iti, Bass Islands, where it is not restricted to the cave environment. This species is considered a Polynesian endemic and it might be present also on other Pacific islands.
